'''Stephens City''' ({{pron-en|<U+02C8>sti<U+02D0>v<U+0259>nz}}) is an [[List of towns in Virginia|incorporated town]] in the southern part of [[Frederick County, Virginia|Frederick County]], [[Virginia]], United States, with a population of 1,146 at the time of the [[2000 United States Census|2000&nbsp;Census]] and an estimated population of 1,503 in 2009.

Founded by [[Peter Stephens (pioneer)|Peter Stephens]] in the 1730s, the colonial town was chartered and named for Lewis Stephens in September&nbsp;1758.  It was originally settled by German [[Protestant]]s from [[Heidelberg]].  Stephens City is the second-oldest municipality in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] after nearby [[Winchester, Virginia|Winchester]], which is about {{convert|5|mi|km}} to the north. "Crossroads", the first [[free black]] community in the Valley in the pre-[[American Civil War|Civil War]] years, was founded east of town in the 1850s.  Crossroads remained until the beginning of the Civil War when the freed blacks either escaped or were recaptured.  Stephens City was saved from being burnt in 1864 by [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] Major Joseph K. Stearns.  The town has gone through several name changes in its history, starting as Stephensburg, then Newtown, and finally winding up as Stephens City, though it nearly became Pantops.  [[Interstate 81]] and [[U.S. Route 11]] pass close to and through the town, respectively.

A large section of the center of the town, including buildings and homes, covering {{convert|65|acre|ha}}, is part of the [[Newtown-Stephensburg Historic District]] and was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1992.  Stephens City celebrated its 250th anniversary on September 1,&nbsp;2008.  The town is a part of the [[Winchester, VA-WV MSA|Winchester, Virginia-West Virginia Metropolitan Statistical Area]], an offshoot of the [[Baltimore<U+2013>Washington Metropolitan Area|Washington<U+2013>Baltimore<U+2013>Northern Virginia, DC<U+2013>MD<U+2013>VA<U+2013>WV Combined Statistical Area]]. It is a member of the Winchester<U+2013>Frederick County Metropolitan Planning Organization.<ref name="WinFredMPO">{{cite web
| url = http://www.winfredmpo.org/mpo_home.asp
| title = Establishment of the Winchester <U+2013> Frederick County (<U+201C>Win-Fred<U+201D>) Metropolitan Planning Organization (MPO)
| accessdate = 2010-04-02
| publisher = Win-Fred MPO
}}</ref>

==History==
===Founding and early days===
Jost Hite, a German immigrant, purchased a large land grant in the northern [[Shenandoah Valley]] in 1731.<ref name="SCHist"/><ref name="SCHist3">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''The Planting of New Virginia: Settlement and Landscape in the Shenandoah Valley'', pages 7<U+2013>9.
| year = 2004
| accessdate = 2010-04-01
| last = Hofstra
| first = Warren R.
| publisher = Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press
}}</ref>  Peter Stephens and a small party of German [[Protestant]]s from [[Heidelberg]], in the [[Palatinate (region)|Palatinate]], arrived about 1732 to buy and settle that land, including the site of what became Stephens City, named for the Stephens family.<ref name="SCHist">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''From the Rhine to the Shenandoah: Eighteenth Century Swiss & German Pioneer Families In the Central Shenandoah Valley of Virginia And their European Origins, vol. 3'', pages 171<U+2013>200.
| year = 2002
| accessdate = 2010-04-01
| last = Bly
| first = Daniel W.
| publisher = Baltimore: Gateway Press
}}</ref><ref name="History">{{cite web
| url = http://www.newtownhistorycenter.org/default.asp?page=504
| title = Town History
| accessdate = 2007-11-17
| last = Smith
| first = Byron C.
| publisher = Newtown History Center in Stephens City, Virginia (released under the [[GFDL]])
}}</ref><ref name="SCHist2">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''The Planting of New Virginia: Settlement and Landscape in the Shenandoah Valley'', pages 34, 94, 98<U+2013>9.
| year = 2004
| accessdate = 2010-04-01
| last = Hofstra
| first = Warren R.
| publisher = Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press
}}</ref>   Although Hite's title to the land was challenged by  [[Thomas Fairfax, 6th Lord Fairfax of Cameron]], the land baron of the area,<ref name="History"/> the matter was settled amicably.<ref name="SCHist4">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''The Planting of New Virginia: Settlement and Landscape in the Shenandoah Valley'', pages 145<U+2013>54.
| year = 2004
| accessdate = 2010-04-01
| last = Hofstra
| first = Warren R.
| publisher = Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press
}}</ref><ref name="SCHist5">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''Virginia Baron: The Story of Thomas 6th Lord Fairfax'', pages 35<U+2013>123, 148<U+2013>9
| year = 1965
| accessdate = 2010-04-01
| last = Brown
| first = Stuart E.
| publisher = Berryville, Virginia: Chesapeake Book Company
}}</ref>

Town lots were laid out beginning in 1754, and in 1758 the [[Virginia General Assembly]] granted a charter for the town of "Stephensburgh".  The mostly German-speaking residents soon left off the "h"; the town was usually spelled "Stephensburg".<ref name = "History"/>  By the start of the [[Revolutionary War]], Stephensburg was often called simply "New Town" or "Newtown", as the new settlement on the [[Great Wagon Road]] south of Winchester.<ref name="History"/> 

Shenandoah Valley and Newtown's central location attracted heavy traffic through the region, and wagon-making emerged as an important industry for the town; Newtown artisans supplied wagons throughout the state.<ref>Joseph Martin, ''A New and Comprehensive Gazetteer of Virginia and the District of Columbia'', (1835)</ref></blockquote>  By 1830, the town's population had reached 800.<ref>Henry Howe, ''Historical Collections of Virginia'' (1845)</ref>  In the late 1850s, free blacks began a settlement about a mile east of town which became known as Crossroads or Freetown.  The community lasted until the Civil War began, when some of the free blacks left for the North; others were captured and forced to fight for the Confederates.<ref name="History"/>

When the [[American Civil War]] broke out in 1861, the majority of Newtown's young men joined [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] forces.<ref name="History"/><ref name="Steele">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''Between the Lines: The Civil War Diaries, Letters and Memoirs of the Steele Family of Newtown/Stephens City, Va., 1861 to 1864''
| accessdate = 
| last = Fravel
| first = Linden A.
| publisher = Date and publisher not recorded, per Newtown History Center <U+2013> Stephens City, Virginia
}}</ref>  During the war, the town was "between the lines",<ref name="Steele"/>  nominally controlled by the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] but with much Confederate [[Partisan (political)|partisan]] activity.<ref name="History"/>  On May 24,&nbsp;1864, [[Stonewall Jackson]]'s Confederate [[Jackson's Valley Campaign|forces]] advanced northward on the Valley Pike and attacked Union troops. At Newtown, General [[George Henry Gordon]] of the [[2nd Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|Second Massachusetts Infantry]] ordered his Federal troops to make a stand.  The skirmishing involved heavy artillery fire, but Gordon's men retreated without loss of the important supply wagons. When Gordon left the town to Jackson's forces, both sides claimed a victory.<ref name="History"/><ref name="Inez">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''Early Days and Methodism in Stephens City, Virginia, 1732<U+2013>1905''
| accessdate = 
| last = Steele
| first = Inez Virginia
| publisher = Geo. F. Norton Publishing Company, 1906. Reprint: Commercial Press, Inc., 1994
}}</ref></blockquote>
[[Image:StephensCity WiddowsFrazierHouse.JPG|thumb|175px|left|The Widdows-Frazier House located along Main Street in Stephens City]]
In June 1864, Major Joseph K. Stearns of the 1st New York Cavalry arrived under orders to burn the town down to help stop Confederate ambushes on the wagon road. Because the remaining population mostly consisted of women, children and the elderly, Stearns allowed the town to stand. He required the adult residents to take the "[[Ironclad oath]]",<ref name="IroncladOath">{{cite web
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=yugEHKEhOnAC&lpg=PA255&ots=Mvfz91n-pp&dq=%22Newtown%22%20%22Virginia%22%20%22Ironclad%20Oath%22&pg=PA192#v=onepage&q&f=false
| title = ''Beleaguered Winchester: a Virginia community at war, 1861<U+2013>1865'', page 192
| year = 2007
| accessdate = 2010-06-01
| last = Duncan
| first = Richard R.
| publisher = Louisiana State University Press
}}</ref><ref name="IroncladOath2">{{cite web
| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=yugEHKEhOnAC&lpg=PA255&ots=Mvfz91n-pp&dq=%22Newtown%22%20%22Virginia%22%20%22Ironclad%20Oath%22&pg=PA255#v=onepage&q&f=false
| title = ''Beleaguered Winchester: a Virginia community at war, 1861<U+2013>1865'', page 255
| year = 2007
| accessdate = 2010-06-01
| last = Duncan
| first = Richard R.
| publisher = Louisiana State University Press
}}</ref> in which they swore that they had not voluntarily provided aid to the Confederacy.  The government required the oath, effectively excluding ex-Confederates from the political arena during [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]].<ref name="History"/>

In April&nbsp;1867, the Virginia General Assembly granted a charter to the Winchester and Strasburg Railroad Company.  The company was authorized to construct a rail line between Winchester and Strasburg, linking Newtown to the rest of the nation by railroad for the first time.  Though the railroad improved the local economy, which had lagged after the end of the war, it decimated the wagon-building trade.<ref name="History"/>  In 1880, the United States Post Office Department, faced with nearly a dozen Newtowns in Virginia, announced that the local post office would be renamed Pantops.  Dissatisfied with the name, the townsfolk chose "Stephens City".<ref name="History"/><ref name="PostOffice">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''Frederick County Post Offices, Past and Present'', pages 43<U+2013>96
| year = 1987
| accessdate = 2008-11-30
| last = Wine
| first = J. Floyd
| publisher = Winchester Frederick County Historical Society Journal 2
}}</ref>

===20th century to present===
The 20th century brought improvements to energy and domestic systems: electrical service was introduced in 1915; and in 1941, just before World War II, the town installed a water system.<ref name="History"/>  The construction of [[Interstate 81]] (I-81) during the early 1960s depressed business development in the town.  The wagon road, which had been made part of [[U.S. Route 11]], had led traffic through the center of town, but the interstate passed less than a tenth of a mile to the east, encouraging development east of town and causing the downtown businesses to decline.  Developers constructed new residential subdivisions both within and outside the town boundaries to the east for access to I-81.<ref name="History"/>  

The town surveyed its older buildings to establish architectural significance and to determine those that contributed to the town's historic center.  The [[Newtown-Stephensburg Historic District]] was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in August&nbsp;1992.<ref name="vaNRHPnom">{{cite web|author=Maral S. Kalbian |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Newtown-Stephensburg Historic District |url= http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Frederick/304-0001_Newtown-Stephensburg_Historic_District_1992_Final_Nomination.pdf |date=October 28, 1991 |accessdate=2010-04-27 |publisher=Virginia Historic Landmarks Commission | format = PDF}} and [http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Frederick/NewtownStephHD_photographs.htm ''Accompanying photo at Virginia Historic Landmarks Commission, undated''] and [http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Counties/Frederick/Newtown_Stephensburg.pdf ''Accompanying map'']</ref>  Renovation of the town center has attracted [[heritage tourism]].  Anticipating more growth, the town annexed {{convert|360|acre|km2|1}} of unincorporated Frederick County in 2005, another {{convert|100|acre|km2|1}} in 2006, and {{convert|175|acre|km2|1}} in 2007.<ref name="History"/>  The town celebrated its 250th anniversary on September 1, 2008.<ref name="250thAnnv">{{cite web
| url = http://www.stephenscity.vi.virginia.gov/pdf/September%20and%20October%20Newsletter%202008.pdf
| title = Stephens City Newsletter
| date = 2008-09
| accessdate = 2010-07-22
| publisher = Town of Stephens City
| format = PDF
}}</ref>

On September 17,&nbsp;2004, remnants of [[Hurricane Ivan]] spawned an [[Fujita scale|F1 tornado]] that touched down just south of the town along Interstate&nbsp;81.  It caused approximately $1&nbsp;million in damage and injured two people.<ref name="AWCTornado">{{cite web
| url = http://www.awc.org/NewsReleases/2004/NewsReleases2004.html#IvanTornado
| title = Hurricane Ivan<U+2019>s Tornado Bands Wreak Havoc in Northern Virginia
| accessdate = 2007-11-24
| publisher = American Wood Council
}}</ref><ref name="SCTornado">{{cite web
| url = http://www.erh.noaa.gov/er/lwx/sept17tornadoes/
| title = National Weather Service Baltimore/Washington
| date = 2004-10-20
| accessdate = 2010-03-26
| publisher = [[National Weather Service]] Baltimore/Washington
}}</ref><ref name="SCTorDam">{{cite web
| url = http://www.erh.noaa.gov/lwx/Storms/Strmdata/storm0904.pdf
| title = Storm Data and Unusual Weather Phenomena
| date = 2004-09
| accessdate = 2010-03-26
| publisher = [[National Weather Service]] Baltimore/Washington
| format = PDF
}}</ref>  It was one of a [[Hurricane Ivan#Rest of the United States|record 40 tornadoes]] to hit northern Virginia that day.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.vdem.state.va.us/newsroom/history/tornado.cfm|title= Virginia Tornadoes |author= Watson, Barbara McNaught |date= 7 January 2008 |work= VAEmergency.com|publisher= Virginia Department of Emergency Management|accessdate=6 April 2010 |quote= Sept. 17, 2004: "Ivan" spawned 29 F0/F1 tornadoes, 10 strong F2 tornadoes and one strong F3 tornado}}</ref>

==Geography==
The town is located between the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]] and the [[Appalachian Mountains]] in the northern [[Shenandoah Valley]] of [[Virginia]] in close proximity to [[West Virginia]], [[Maryland]], and [[Pennsylvania]]. [[Washington, D.C.]] is approximately {{convert|65.9|mi|km}} to the west<ref name="Geography">{{cite web
| url = http://www.city-data.com/city/Stephens-City-Virginia.html
| title = Nearest city with pop. 200,000+
| accessdate = 2010-05-31
| publisher = City-Data.com
}}</ref> and [[Baltimore]] is {{convert|84|mi|km}} to the northwest.<ref name="Geography2">{{cite web
| url = http://www.geobytes.com/CityDistanceTool.htm?d&pt_1=usvascit&pt_2=usmdbali
| title = The distance between Stephens City, Virginia and Baltimore, Maryland 
| date = 2010-05-31
| accessdate = 2010-05-31
| publisher = Geobytes
}}</ref>

===Climate===
Stephens City is located in the [[humid subtropical climate]] zone ([[K<U+00F6>ppen climate classification]]: ''Cfa''), exhibiting four distinct seasons.<ref name="Koppen">{{cite web
| url = http://koeppen-geiger.vu-wien.ac.at/
| title = World Map of the K<U+00F6>ppen-Geiger climate classification updated
| date = 2008-11-06
| accessdate = 2010-03-23
| publisher = University of Veterinary Medicine Vienna
}}</ref>  Its climate is typical of Mid-Atlantic U.S. areas removed from bodies of water.  The town is located in plant [[hardiness zone]]&nbsp;7 throughout the town and surrounding Frederick County, indicating a temperate climate.<ref name="HZone">{{cite web
| url = http://www.arborday.org/media/zones.cfm
| title = Hardiness Zones
| year = 2006
| accessdate = 2010-03-23
| publisher = Arbor Day Foundation
}}</ref>  Spring and fall are warm, with low humidity, while winter is cool, with annual snowfall averaging {{convert|15.0|in|cm}}.<ref name="SCSnowAvg">{{cite web
| url = http://www.erh.noaa.gov/er/lwx/Historic_Events/va-winters.htm
| title = Virginia Winters
| date = 2005-12-30
| accessdate = 2010-03-23
| last = McNaught Watson
| first = Barbara
| publisher = National Weather Service <U+2013> Weather Forecast Office Baltimore/Washington
}}</ref> Average winter lows tend to be around 30&nbsp;<U+00B0>F (<U+2212>1&nbsp;<U+00B0>C) from mid-December to mid-February.  Blizzards affect Stephens City on average once every four to six years. The most violent [[nor'easter]]s typically feature high winds, heavy rains, and occasional snow. These storms often affect large sections of the U.S. East Coast.<ref name="SCSnowAvg"/>

Summers are hot and humid; during this season, highs average in the upper&nbsp;80s <U+00B0>F (lower&nbsp;30s <U+00B0>C) and lows average in the upper&nbsp;60s <U+00B0>F (lower&nbsp;20s <U+00B0>C).<ref name="Weather">{{cite web
| url = http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/22655
| title = Monthly Averages for Stephens City, VA
| date = 2010-03-23
| accessdate = 2010-03-23
| publisher = The Weather Channel Interactive, Inc.
}}</ref>  The combination of heat and humidity in the summer brings very frequent thunderstorms, some of which occasionally produce tornadoes in the area.  While hurricanes (or their remnants) occasionally track through the area in late summer and early fall, they have often weakened by the time they reach Stephens City, partly due to the city's far inland location.
The highest recorded temperature was {{convert|105|F|C|abbr=on}} in&nbsp;1918,&nbsp;1988, and again in&nbsp;2010, while the lowest recorded temperature was {{convert|-18|F|C|abbr=on}} in&nbsp;1983.<ref name=Weather />

