==Demographics==
As of the 2000 U.S. [[census]],{{GR|2}} there were 1,146&nbsp;people, 500&nbsp;households, and 291&nbsp;families residing in the town.<ref name=2000Census>{{cite web |url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/QTTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=16000US5175344&-qr_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_DP1&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U&-_lang=en&-_sse=on |title = DP-1. Profile of General Demographic Characteristics:  2000 |date = 2000-12 |accessdate = 2010-03-24 |publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>  The 2009 population estimate showed 1,503 people living in the town, an increase of 31.15% from the year 2000.<ref name="Estimates">{{cite web | url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/SAFFPopulation?_event=Search&geo_id=01000US&_geoContext=01000US&_street=&_county=Stephens+City&_cityTown=Stephens+City&_state=04000US51&_zip=&_lang=en&_sse=on&ActiveGeoDiv=geoSelect&_useEV=&pctxt=fph&pgsl=010&_submenuId=population_0&ds_name=null&_ci_nbr=null&qr_name=null&reg=null%3Anull&_keyword=&_industry= | title = Population Finder |year = 2000 | accessdate = 2010-03-24 | publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>  In 2000, [[population density]] was 112 people per square mile.<ref name="PPSqMile">{{cite web |url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/ThematicMapFramesetServlet?_bm=y&-PANEL_ID=tm_result&-_MapEvent=displayBy&-tm_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_M00090&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U&-tm_config=|b=50|l=en|t=4001|zf=0.0|ms=thm_def|dw=0.05177227511536533|dh=0.02986148887021128|dt=gov.census.aff.domain.map.EnglishMapExtent|if=gif|cx=-78.22503449999999|cy=39.0908745|zl=3|pz=3|bo=|bl=|ft=350:349:335:389:388:332:331|fl=403:381:204:380:369:379:368|g=16000US5175344|ds=DEC_2000_SF1_U|sb=50|tud=false|db=140|mn=112|mx=112|cc=1|cm=1|cn=5|cb=|um=Persons/Sq%20Mile|pr=0|th=DEC_2000_SF1_U_M00090|sf=N|sg=&-redoLog=false&-errMsg=&-geo_id=16000US5175344&-_dBy=140&-_sse=on&-_lang=en
| title = TM-P002. Persons per Square Mile: 2000 |date = 2000-12 |accessdate = 2010-03-24 |publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>  The racial makeup of the town was 89.9%&nbsp;[[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 6.5%&nbsp;[[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.4%&nbsp;[[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.6%&nbsp;[[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], and 1.6%&nbsp;from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]].  [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 2.0%&nbsp;of the population.<ref name="RaceGender">{{cite web
| url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/SAFFFacts?_event=Search&geo_id=&_geoContext=&_street=&_county=Stephens+City&_cityTown=Stephens+City&_state=04000US51&_zip=&_lang=en&_sse=on&pctxt=fph&pgsl=010&show_2003_tab=&redirect=Y
| title = Census 2000 Demographic Profile Highlights
| date = 2000-12
| accessdate = 2010-08-13
| publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]
}}</ref>  There were 531&nbsp;males and 615&nbsp;females residing in the town.<ref name="RaceGender"/>

There were 500&nbsp;households out of which 26.8% had children under the age of&nbsp;18 living with them, 43.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 41.8% were non-families.<ref name="Ages">{{cite web
|url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/QTTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=16000US5175344&-qr_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_QTP1&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U&-_lang=en&-redoLog=false&-CONTEXT=qt |title = QT-P1. Age Groups and Sex:  2000 |date = 2000-12 |accessdate = 2010-03-26 |publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>  50.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 20.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.<ref name="Ages"/> The average household size was 2.29 and the average family size was 2.97.<ref name=2000Census/> The population of the town was spread out with 23.7% under the age of 18, 8.8% from 18 to 24, 32.5% from 25 to 44, 23.8% from 45 to 64, and 11.1% who were 6&nbsp;years of age or older.<ref name="Ages"/> The median age was 35.6 years.<ref name="Ages"/> The median income for a household in the town was $35,200, and the median income for a family was $41,827.  Employed males had a median income of $29,432 versus $22,313 for employed females.  The [[per capita income]] for the city was $17,998.<ref name="Income">{{cite web
| url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/QTTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=16000US5175344&-qr_name=DEC_2000_SF4_U_DP3&-reg=DEC_2000_SF4_U_DP3:001&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF4_U&-_lang=en&-redoLog=true&-format=&-CONTEXT=qt |title = DP-3. Profile of Selected Economic Characteristics:  2000 |date = 2000-12 |accessdate = 2010-03-26 |publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>

On the 2000&nbsp;Census, residents self-identified with a variety of ethnic ancestries; the major categories reflect the settlers of the 18th and early 19th century.  People of [[German American|German]] descent make up 17.6% of the population of the town, with [[American ethnicity|American]] at 14.7%, [[English American|English]] at 11.2%, [[Irish American|Irish]] at 8.9%, [[Scotch-Irish American|Scotch-Irish]] at 1.8%, [[Dutch American|Dutch]] at 1.4%, [[European American|European]] at 1.4%, [[French American|French]] at 1.3%, [[Italian American|Italian]] at 1.3%, [[Scottish American|Scottish]] at 1.0%, [[Norwegian American|Norwegian]] at 0.7%, [[Swedish American|Swedish]] at 0.6%, [[Canadian American|Canadian]] at 0.5%, [[Polish American|Polish]] at 0.4%, [[Slavic Americans|Slavic]] at 0.4%, [[Sub-Saharan Africa|Subsaharan African]] at 0.4%, Celtic at 0.2%, [[Czech American|Czechoslovakian]] at 0.2%, [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] at 0.2%, [[Romanian American|Romanian]] at 0.2%, and [[Slovak American|Slovak]] rounding out at 0.1%.  20.0%&nbsp;of the population of the town are of "other ancestries".<ref name="Ancestry">{{cite web
| url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/QTTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=16000US5175344&-qr_name=DEC_2000_SF3_U_QTP13&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF3_U
| title = QT-P13. Ancestry:  2000
| date = 2000-12
| accessdate = 2010-04-07
| publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]
}}</ref>

==Economy==
[[Image:StephensCity FamilyDriveIn.JPG|thumb|175px|right|The Family Drive-In Theatre, located just south of Stephens City, Virginia]]
The economy of Stephens City features several industries.<ref name="Economy">{{cite web
| url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/QTTable?_bm=y&-geo_id=16000US5175344&-qr_name=DEC_2000_SF3_U_DP3&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF3_U&-_lang=en&-_sse=on
| title = DP-3. Profile of Selected Economic Characteristics:  2000
| date = 2000-12
| accessdate = 2010-07-25
| publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]]
}}</ref>  According to the [[2000 United States Census]], the industries in the town (by percentage of employed civilian population 16&nbsp;years and over) were manufacturing at 20.4%, educational, health and social services with 19.9%, retail trade at 12.8%, arts, entertainment, recreation, accommodation and food services with 9.0%, construction at 8.0%, other services (except public administration) with 6.8%, transportation, warehousing, and utilities at 4.6%, public administration with 3.9%, professional, scientific, management, administrative, and waste management services at 3.7%, finance, insurance, real estate, and rental and leasing with 3.4%, wholesale trade at 3.4%, information with 2.2% and agriculture, forestry, fishing and hunting, and mining at 1.9%.<ref name="Economy"/>

Of the people in the [[labor force]] in the town over the age of&nbsp;16, the majority, 597 people or 66.1% of the population, were in the civilian work force, while 306 people, or 33.9%, of the population were not in the labor force at all.  At the time of the Census, only nine people, or 1.0%, were unemployed, with none in the [[United States armed forces|Armed Forces]].  Of the 588 residents employed age 16 and over, private-sector wage and salary workers accounted for 457 of them or 77.7%.  Ninety-five people were classified as [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] workers, or 16.2% of the population, with the self-employed making up 5.8% of the population or 34&nbsp;people.  Two people, or 0.3%, of the population were classified as unpaid workers.<ref name="Economy"/>

The [[median household income]] for the town of Stephens City was $35,200, with the majority, 126 persons, or 24.8%, of the population in that class of income.  Eighty people, or 15.7%, identified themselves as retired.<ref name="Economy"/>

==Culture==
[[Image:StephensCity NewtownCommons.JPG|thumb|175px|left|View of Newtown Commons, located along Main Street (US 11) in Stephens City]]
Town residents have access to two parks within town limits: Newtown Commons and Bel Air Street Park.  Newtown Commons, sometimes called Newtown Park, is located along Main Street, and the other is on Bel Air Street.<ref name="ParksRec">{{cite web
| url = http://www.stephenscity.vi.virginia.gov/faq.shtml
| title = Frequently Asked Questions 
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = Town of Stephens City
}}</ref>  At Newtown Commons, residents can hold outdoor events such as picnics, fundraisers or small concerts.  The Bel Air Street Park is a playground for children with standard swingsets and other activities.<ref name="ParksRec"/>

Just outside Stephens City is Sherando Park.  The park houses several trails, ponds, a pool, sports fields and more.<ref name="SherandoPark">{{cite web
| url = http://www.co.frederick.va.us/parks/sherandopark.aspx
| title = Parks and Recreation <U+2013> Sherando Park
| accessdate = 2010-04-12
| publisher = Frederick County, Virginia Parks and Recreation
}}</ref>  Sherando Park is also home of the Virginia Tech Memorial Garden, planted in memory of the 2007 [[Virginia Tech massacre]], which took place approximately {{convert|175|mi|km}} from the park. It has "a winding sidewalk shaped in the college's trademark 'VT'" and "a flagpole surrounded by 32 [[Hokie Stone]]s", one for each of the 32 victims of the shooting.<ref name="VTMemPark">{{cite web
| url = http://www.alumni.vt.edu/chapters/newsletters/august2009.html
| title = Chapter Highlight: Shenandoah Garden
| date = 2009-08
| accessdate = 2010-04-12
| publisher = Virginia Tech Alumni Association
}}</ref><ref name="VTMemPark2">{{cite web
| url = http://shenandoahhokies.com/garden.htm
| title = Memorial Garden
| accessdate = 2010-04-12
| publisher = Shenandoah Chapter <U+2013> Virginia Tech Alumni Association
}}</ref>  The Memorial Garden was opened on April 16, 2009, the second anniversary of the shooting.<ref name="VTMemPark"/>  The park was built by the Shenandoah Chapter of Virginia Tech Alumni Association, which is based in nearby [[Winchester, Virginia]].<ref name="VTMemPark2"/>

The Family Drive-In Theatre, a two-screen [[drive-in theater]], is located near the town, on [[U.S. Route 11]] just south of Stephens City.<ref name="SCDriveIn">{{cite web
| url = http://www.thefamilydriveintheatre.com/
| title = Family Drive-In Theatre
| date = 2010-05-31
| accessdate = 2010-05-31
| publisher = Family Drive-In Theatre
}}</ref> It is one of eight drive-ins in the state of Virginia.<ref name="DriveInVA">{{cite web
| url = http://www.driveinmovie.com/VA.htm
| title = Drive-ins in Virginia
| accessdate = 2010-03-25
| publisher = DriveInMovie.com
}}</ref><ref name="DriveInVA2">{{cite web
| url = http://www.driveintheater.com/drivlist.htm
| title = Drive-In List
| accessdate = 2010-03-25
| publisher = DriveInTheater.com
}}</ref>  Stephens City is also the location of the annual "Newtown Heritage Festival" held each [[Memorial Day]] weekend.  The two-day event features many crafts, a tractor wagon ride through town, bluegrass music at Newtown Commons and a parade on Saturday.<ref name="Festival">{{cite web
| url = http://www.stephenscity.vi.virginia.gov/newtownheritage.shtml
| title = Newtown Heritage Festival 
| accessdate = 2010-03-26
| publisher = Town of Stephens City
}}</ref>

Stephens City is one of the towns along the [[Garage sale#Route 11 Yard Crawl|Route 11 Yard Crawl]].  A yearly event held during the second Saturday in August, the Yard Crawl is an almost 50-mile-long (80&nbsp;km) [[yard sale]] that stretches from Stephens City's Newtown Commons south along U.S. Route 11 to [[New Market, Virginia]].<ref name="YardCrawl">{{cite web
| url = http://www.nvdaily.com/news/2010/08/organizers-ready-for-sixth-annual-route-11-crawl.php
| title = Organizers ready for sixth annual Route 11 crawl
| date = 2010-08-09
| accessdate = 2010-08-09
| last = Knight
| first = Preston
| publisher = ''Northern Virginia Daily''
}}</ref>  The event is sponsored by the [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Shenandoah County]] Chamber Advisory Group, five chambers of commerce, and the town of Stephens City<ref name="YardCrawl2">{{cite web
| url = http://www.shenandoahtravel.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=79:shenandoah-countys-route-11-yard-crawla-weekend-to-remember
| title = Shenandoah County's Route 11 Yard Crawl...A weekend to remember 
| date = 2010-08-09
| accessdate = 2010-08-09
| last = Wood Monroe, Jennifer
| first = Zimmerman, Hank
| publisher = Shenandoah County Tourism
}}</ref>  In years past, the Yard Crawl has attracted interest from people as far away as Canada.<ref name="YardCrawl"/>

Nearby [[Winchester, Virginia]]<U+2014>about {{convert|5|mi|km}} to the north<U+2014>is home to the [[Winchester Royals]],<ref name="WincRoyals">{{cite web
| url = http://www.valleyleaguebaseball.com/teams/winchester/index
| title = Winchester Royals
| accessdate = 2010-07-28
| publisher = Valley Baseball League
}}</ref> which is part of the [[Valley Baseball League]], a [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]-sanctioned [[List of collegiate summer baseball leagues|collegiate summer baseball league]] in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] of Virginia.<ref name="AboutVBL">{{cite web
| url = http://www.valleyleaguebaseball.com/information/about_vbl
| title = About the VBL
| accessdate = 2010-07-28
| publisher = Valley Baseball League
}}</ref>

==Government==
[[Image:StephensCity TownOffices.JPG|thumb|175px|left|The Town Government Offices of Stephens City are located along Locust Street.]]
The head of Stephens City's government is Mayor Joy B. Shull, a former member of the Town Council, who was elected in an unopposed May 4,&nbsp;2010 election, and is serving four years as mayor.<ref name="Shull">{{cite news
| url = http://sherandotimes.com/Sherando20100428_web.pdf
| title = Meet Stephens City<U+2019>s next mayor
| date = 2010-04-28
| accessdate = 2010-05-04
| last = Davis
| first = Brandon
| work = The Sherando Times
| format = PDF
}}</ref>  Shull succeeded Ray E. Ewing, who had served since&nbsp;1994,<ref name="MayorYears">{{cite web
| url = http://www.stephenscity.vi.virginia.gov/pdf/Newsletter/January%20and%20February%20Newsletter%202010.pdf
| title = Stephens City Newsletter, Volume 29, Issue 1, January and February 2010
| date = 2001-10-20
| accessdate = 2010-03-24
| publisher = Town of Stephens City, Virginia
| format = PDF
}}</ref><ref name="ShullsSpot"/> and retired at the end of his term.<ref name="MayorRetire">{{cite news
| url = http://www.nvdaily.com/news/2010/04/candidates-ready-for-council-elections.php
| title = Candidates ready for council elections
| date = 2010-07-22
| accessdate = 2010-04-29
| last = Williams
| first = J. R.
| work = Northern Virginia Daily
}}</ref> The representative body of Stephens City is known as the Town Council, whose members as of 2010 include Ronald
Bowers, Linden A. Fravel, Jr., James H. Harter, Joseph Hollis, and Martha W. Dilg.<ref name="MayorTCComm">{{cite web
| url = http://www.stephenscity.vi.virginia.gov/towncouncil.shtml
| title = Town Council
| date = 
| accessdate = 2010-03-24
| publisher = Town of Stephens City, Virginia
}}</ref>  Dilg was elected in a May 4,&nbsp;2010, election to succeed Michael Grim, who left the Town Council at the end of his term.<ref name="May4Election">{{cite web
| url = https://www.voterinfo.sbe.virginia.gov/election/DATA/2010/A470CCC2-6F4F-4635-BB89-526338D1B403/Unofficial/00_069_s.shtml
| title = May 4, 2010 Town Elections Unofficial Results
| date = 2010-05-04
| accessdate = 2010-05-04
| publisher = Virginia State Board of Elections
}}</ref>  Shull's replacement on Town Council was originally to be decided at a May 5,&nbsp;2010, Town Council meeting<ref name="ShullsSpot">{{cite news
| url = http://www.nvdaily.com/news/2010/05/stephens-city-picks-new-mayor.php
| title = Stephens City picks new mayor
| date = 2010-05-05
| accessdate = 2010-05-05
| work = Northern Virginia Daily
}}</ref> but was not announced until June 29,&nbsp;2010, when Joseph Grayson was officially named to fill Shull's seat.<ref name="ShullsSpot2">{{cite news
| url = http://www.nvdaily.com/news/2010/06/shull-sworn-in-as-mayor-of-town.php
| title = Shull sworn in as mayor of town
| date = 2010-06-29
| accessdate = 2010-06-30
| work = Northern Virginia Daily
}}</ref>

As of&nbsp;2010, the town is served by Police Chief Charles Bockey and Fire Chief Greg Locke, both of whom are on the town's Public Safety Committee.<ref name="MayorTCComm"/>  The town is served by five other committees: the Administrative Committee, the Personnel Committee, the Water and Sewer Committee, the Public Works Committee, and the Finance Committee.<ref name="MayorTCComm"/>  The members of those five committees are composed of Town Council members.<ref name="MayorTCComm"/>

Stephens City is represented by [[Clay Athey|Clifford L. "Clay" Athey]], ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) in the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] 18th&nbsp;District.<ref name="Legislator">{{cite web
| url = http://capwiz.com/valcvef/directory/statedir.tt?lvl=state&state=VA&myaddress=1033%20Locust%20Street&mycity=Stephens%20City&mystate=VA
| title = Virginia State Legislative Directory
| date = 2010-07-25
| accessdate = 2010-07-25
| publisher = Virginia League of Conservation Voters
}}</ref>  [[Jill Holtzman Vogel]] (Republican) represents the town in the [[Senate of Virginia|Virginia Senate]]'s 27th District.<ref name="Legislator"/>  The town is represented by [[Frank Wolf|Frank R. Wolf]] (Republican) in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] from Virginia's [[Virginia's 10th congressional district|10th district]].<ref name="RepSen">{{cite web
| url = http://www.congress.org/congressorg/officials/congress/?view=myofficials&azip=22655&bzip=&lvl=L&submit.x=22&submit.y=13&submit=go
| title = Elected Officials-Virginia (22655)
| date = 2010-07-25
| accessdate = 2010-07-25
| publisher = CQ-Roll Call, Inc.
}}</ref>  [[Jim Webb]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]) and [[Mark Warner]] (Democrat) represent the town in the [[United States Senate]].<ref name="RepSen"/>

==Education==
[[Frederick County Public Schools (Virginia)|Frederick County Public Schools]] operate the public schools that serve Stephens City, although none is located within Stephens City proper;  public schools that serve Stephens City are within a mile of the town limits.  The town and surrounding area are served by Bass-Hoover Elementary School,<ref name="BassHoover">{{cite web
| url = http://www.frederick.k12.va.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=8
| title = Bass-Hoover Elementary School
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = Frederick County Public Schools
}}</ref> Robert E. Aylor Middle School,<ref name="Aylor">{{cite web
| url = http://www.frederick.k12.va.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=19
| title = Robert E. Aylor Middle School
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = Frederick County Public Schools
}}</ref> and [[Sherando High School]].<ref name="Sherando">{{cite web
| url = http://www.frederick.k12.va.us/education/school/school.php?sectionid=24
| title = Sherando High School
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = Frederick County Public Schools
}}</ref>  The latter was named for one of the historic [[Iroquoian]]-speaking tribes encountered by early European settlers to the Shenandoah Valley. Local private schools are available, and are also outside the town's corporate limits.  Shenandoah Valley Christian Academy is located at the northern section of the town limits.<ref name="SVCA">{{cite web
| url = http://www.svca.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48&Itemid=56
| title = Directions/Map 
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = Shenandoah Valley Christian Academy
}}</ref>  Powhatan School is in nearby [[Boyce, Virginia|Boyce]] in [[Clarke County, Virginia]].<ref name="Powhatan">{{cite web
| url = http://www.powhatanschool.org/about/directions.php
| title = Directions
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = Powhatan School
}}</ref>  Other smaller private or Christian-based schools are located throughout Frederick County and elsewhere in the area.

==Transportation==
Historic [[U.S. Route 11]] traverses Stephens City proper, while [[Interstate 81]] serves as the eastern border of the town.<ref name="US11I81">{{cite web
| url = http://gis.co.frederick.va.us/Freeance/Client/PublicAccess1/index.html?appconfig=StephensCity
| title = Welcome to the Frederick County Interactive Mapping Website
| accessdate = 2010-03-26
| publisher = Frederick County Information Technologies GIS Division
}}</ref>  Stephens City serves as the western terminus of [[Virginia State Route 277|State Route 277]], which begins at U.S. Route 11 and ends only {{convert|4.72|mi|km}} away in [[Double Tollgate, Virginia|Double Tollgate]], [[Clarke County, Virginia]] at [[United States Numbered Highways|U.S. Routes]] [[U.S. Route 340|340]] and [[U.S. Route 522|522]].<ref name="VA277Map">{{cite web
| url = http://www.vahighways.com/route-log/va261-280.htm#va277
| title = VA 261 to 280
| date = 2008-10-30
| accessdate = 2010-03-26
| publisher = Adam Froehlig and Mike Roberson
}}</ref>

Plans are in place to move State Route&nbsp;277 to near The Family Drive-In Theatre, {{convert|0.50|mi|km}} south of its current western terminus with US Route 11.  The eastern terminus will be near Lake Frederick at [[US Route 522]] in Clarke County near the Warren County line.<ref name="277Move">{{cite web
| url = http://www.co.frederick.va.us/planning/SpecialProjects/277/images/RT277_Transportation_FINAL_11x17_100808.jpg
| title = Route 277 Triangle & Urban Center Study: Proposed Transportation Study & Trail Network <U+2013> Final
| accessdate = 2008-10-10
| publisher = Frederick County (Virginia) Department of Planning and Development
}}</ref>  The planned construction will also move the [[Interstate 81|I-81]] interchange at Stephens City, where there are a number of service stations and fast food restaurants, south of the town limits to alleviate congestion on the current Route&nbsp;277 bridge, which will remain after construction is completed.  Planners expect expansion of Stephens City to the south.<ref name="277Move"/>

==Religion==
[[Image:StephensCity TrinityLutheran.JPG|175px|right|thumb|Trinity Lutheran Church along Fairfax Street in Stephens City]]
A 2000&nbsp;study by the [[Glenmary Home Missioners|Glenmary Research Center]] assessed the religious preferences of the residents of Stephens City.  It found that 33.2% attended the [[United Methodist Church]], 13.6% attended the [[Presbyterianism|Presbyterian Church]], 9.5% were adherent to the [[Southern Baptist Convention]], 8.1% attended the [[Church of God (Cleveland, Tennessee)|Church of God]], 6.5% attended non-charismatic or independent churches, 5.8% attended the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]], 5.5% attended the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]], 5.0% attended [[Christian Church]]es and [[Churches of Christ]], 3.1% attended [[Assemblies of God]] and 9.7% were adherent to another denomination.<ref name="CongMem">{{cite web
| url = 
| title = ''Congregations and Membership in the United States''
| year = 2000
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| last = Jones
| first = Dale E.
| publisher = [[Glenmary Home Missioners|Glenmary Research Center]]
}}</ref><ref name="CongMem2">{{cite web
| url = http://www.city-data.com/city/Stephens-City-Virginia.html
| title = Religion statistics for Stephens City
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = City-Data.com
}}</ref>

The town includes churches of the [[Baptists|Baptist]], [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]], [[Mennonite]], [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] and [[Methodism|United Methodist]] denominations of Christianity,<ref name="Churches">{{cite web
| url = http://www.stephenscity.vi.virginia.gov/schoolsandchurches.shtml
| title = Schools and Churches 
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = Town of Stephens City
}}</ref> plus a [[Unitarian Universalism|Unitarian Universalist]] church.<ref name="UUCSV">{{cite web
| url = http://www.uushenandoah.org/wheressc.shtml
| title = Where is the UUCSV?
| accessdate = 2010-04-06
| publisher = Unitarian Universalist Church of the Shenandoah Valley
}}</ref>  Other religious organizations are located outside the town limits, including [[Catholic]],<ref name="Catholic">{{cite web
| url = http://www.sacredheartwinchester.org/
| title = Sacred Heart of Jesus Roman Catholic Church 
| accessdate = 2010-08-13
| publisher = Sacred Heart of Jesus Roman Catholic Church
}}</ref> [[Judaism|Jewish]],<ref name="Judaism">{{cite web
| url = http://www.bethelcongregation.org/
| title = Beth El Congregation
| accessdate = 2010-08-13
| publisher = Beth El Congregation
}}</ref> and [[Islam|Muslim]]<ref name="Islam">{{cite web
| url = http://www.iswinchester.com/
| title = Islamic Society of Winchester
| accessdate = 2010-08-13
| publisher = Islamic Society of Winchester
}}</ref> bodies which are located about {{convert|5|mi|km}} to the north in [[Winchester, Virginia]].

==Notable residents==
